03974nam a22005775i 9780300151732DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20082008ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001517327 a10.12987/97803001517322doi  a(DE-B1597)486478  a(OCoLC)884499444  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 4aQL673b.W48 2008eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a704.9/43282221 aKeddie, Nikki R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHumans, Nature, and Birds :bScience Art from Cave Walls to Computer Screens /cNikki R. Keddie. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword: Art, Science, and Birds -- tPreface: What Is Science Art? -- tIntroduction: A Gallery of Science Art -- tGallery Guide -- tLower Gallery -- tMezzanine -- tUpper Gallery -- tAppendix 1. Timeline Linking Art, Technology, and the Study of Birds -- tAppendix 2. A Science Art Checklist for Practitioners -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tAcknowledgments -- tIllustration Credits -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book invites readers to enter a two-floor virtual "gallery" where 60-plus images of birds reflecting the accomplishments of human pictorial history are on display. These are works in a genre the authors term Science Art-that is, art that says something about the natural world and how it works. Darryl Wheye and Donald Kennedy show how these works of art can advance our understanding of the ways nature has been perceived over time, its current vulnerability, and our responsibility to preserve its wealth. Each room in the gallery is dedicated to a single topic. The rooms on the first floor show birds as icons, birds as resources, birds as teaching tools, and more. On the second floor, the images and their captions clarify what Science Art is and how the intertwining of art and science can change the way we look at each. The authors also provide a timeline linking scientific innovations with the production of images of birds, and they offer a checklist of steps to promote the creation and accessibility of Science Art. Readers who tour this unique and fascinating gallery will never look at art depicting nature in the same way again. Published with assistance from the Alfred P. Sloan Foundation's Public Understanding of Science and Technology Program.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aArt and science. 0aBirds in art. 0aNature (Aesthetics) 0aNaturexEffect of human beings on. 0aOrnithological illustration. 0aOrnithology. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300151732423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300151732.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles